00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:52.000
so at first I'm going to tell you

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:54.000
why maybe tidymodels and actually

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:56.000
Carrot too exist

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:58.000
R is very very very good at

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.000
many types of modeling

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
it's always been stellar at things like

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:04.000
mixed models and hierarchical models

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.000
survival analysis

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:08.000
and there are just so many things that it does

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:10.000
in terms of modeling

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:12.000
for a long time it's had quite a long

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:14.000
history of having really good predictive modeling

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:16.000
and machine learning models

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:18.000
so there's a lot of really good things if you're doing

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:20.000
modeling in R

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.000
you know the formula interface if you ever use that

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:24.000
like y tilde x

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:26.000
that's been around since I think it was like 1982

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:28.000
believe it or not in the S language

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:30.000
and so all the things they did

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.000
back then in the S language have really carried through

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:34.000
R and so we've always

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.000
benefited from having really expressive ways

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.000
to do modeling

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:40.000
and it's also pretty much had cutting edge models

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:42.000
so things like random forest the first

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.000
real implementation of that that people could

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:46.000
use that wasn't Fortran was

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:48.000
built in R and so a lot of times

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:50.000
people who do modeling they might use

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.000
R as their first sort of like

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:54.000
prototyping language

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:56.000
so outside of like deep learning and some

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:58.000
other things especially as tree based

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:00.000
models and regularized models

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:02.000
I think you see things in R before you see them

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:04.000
anywhere else and if they're not there

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:06.000
the last really good thing that's pointed out here

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:08.000
is R and the S language

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:10.000
originally was built as an interface

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:12.000
to Fortran wrappers if you can believe that

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.000
so for quite a while in the

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:16.000
DNA of R and S

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.000
it's always been really easy to take

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.000
things that R doesn't do well

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:22.000
and do them much faster or better

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:24.000
in C or Java or Python

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:26.000
or whatever it is and so

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
there's quite a lot there to love

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.000
and use and

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.000
it can be very effective with it

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:34.000
but there is a downside and it's mostly

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:36.000
about consistency and so

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:38.000
you know some examples

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:40.000
that I'll go into a little bit more

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:42.000
detail

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:44.000
come down to things where I think package

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:46.000
managers and I'll include myself in

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:48.000
here early on

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
I think when we write packages we

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:52.000
kind of write them for ourselves usually

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:54.000
and so a lot of times

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:56.000
the scope of the package or the

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:58.000
things it can do or the things that it doesn't do

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.000
a lot of times it's largely informed

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:02.000
by the things that are important to us at the

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.000
moment right so

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
who we work with

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.000
you know one said you know I really

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.000
wanted to eventually write a package that I love

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:12.000
that nobody knows about right

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.000
and so what happens sometimes is somebody writes an interesting

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:16.000
modeling package but there's a lot of things

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:18.000
that other people might want to do that maybe

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:20.000
they don't know about or haven't thought about and it doesn't

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:22.000
really get implemented in the package and that can

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
make it kind of difficult to use sometimes

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:26.000
so just some examples

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
of the consistency problem

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.000
let's say you're fitting a classification

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
model and let's say you have like

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:34.000
two classes like yes or no and

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.000
you want to get the class probabilities back

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.000
you might start off by fitting like

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:40.000
an old school like linear discriminant model

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.000
and the standard way of doing

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.000
that is to take that model fit and put it into the

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.000
predict function and if you use that

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:48.000
particular model and you want to get the probabilities

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:50.000
back you don't really have to do anything you can

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.000
just use the predict function

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.000
and give it your object but for a lot

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:56.000
of other models you have to say something like type

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:58.000
equal and this is just

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:00.000
this slide is usually a lot longer

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.000
with all the options

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.000
you have but you know there's type equal response

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:06.000
for logistic regression there's

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:08.000
sometimes it's prob which is the one I like

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:10.000
sometimes it's posterior

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.000
sometimes it's probability so

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.000
you know when I was doing this for a living like

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.000
in before

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:18.000
2000 I'm old

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:20.000
you know this is very very frustrating because you

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:22.000
have to remember all the minutiae of every

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.000
particular package that you would like to try

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:26.000
and that was kind of a pain

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:28.000
the other thing is R

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
generally has two interfaces

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.000
the models there's the formula method

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:34.000
that I discussed and then there's also

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:36.000
what we just really call like the non formula method

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:38.000
and that's where you have

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:40.000
predictors in some matrix or data frame

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:42.000
x in your outcome in some

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:44.000
vector or matrix or whatever y

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:46.000
and then you'd say the function

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
and give it x and y

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.000
and sometimes you want one

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.000
or the other or sometimes you might want

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
both depending on how your data come in

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
and things like that and so here are five

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:58.000
fairly popular machine

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:00.000
learning or modeling

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.000
packages and

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:06.000
let's pick glimnet

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:08.000
so between the formula method

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:10.000
and the non formula method raise your hand

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:12.000
if you think it has the formula method

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.000
okay thank you raise your hand

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:18.000
if you think it has the non formula method

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:20.000
okay wow

