all shakes out so if you're using glimnet

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.000
it actually only takes matrices

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:30.000
which is kind of a pain because if you have

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.000
any categorical predictors

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.000
it's your job to turn that into

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:36.000
indicator variables if you want to transform

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.000
a variable that's your problem

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.000
the formula method kind of does that

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:42.000
automatically for you and then you have to

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.000
when you make new predictions give it

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:46.000
a matrix and it's very limiting

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:48.000
so if your data is not just

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.000
a bunch of numbers already that

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.000
you know you do the work

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.000
so you know we get around that but

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:56.000
it is what it is

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.000
rangers are really good random forest package

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:00.000
it's pretty fast and it does a lot of

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:02.000
things and it has both the formula method and the

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:04.000
non formula method which actually is not correct

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:06.000
you can use the formula or use

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:08.000
x and y the problem is

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.000
it's all in one function so they have a function

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:12.000
that have arguments formula and data

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:14.000
and x and y

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:16.000
which is kind of weird but we can get there

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.000
our part is

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.000
a decision tree package

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:22.000
very old it has just the formula method

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:24.000
I long ago

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:26.000
put in an issue to get the non formula package

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.000
or non formula interface

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:30.000
and the maintainer sent me

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:32.000
the sources and says you should maintain it

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.000
then I am not maintaining

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:36.000
it and then survival

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
is for survival package

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.000
it is also formula only and then

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:42.000
XGBoost which a lot of people love

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:44.000
not only does it not have

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:46.000
a formula method you have to convert the

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:48.000
data to a special sparse matrix format

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.000
you append

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.000
your outcome to that

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:54.000
and if it is a classification model

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:56.000
you have to convert your outcome to zero based integers

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.000
so this just gives you a sense

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
that these are all used quite a bit

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:02.000
all these packages

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:04.000
so sometimes you are doing a lot of work

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:06.000
for these packages

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.000
so this isn't really something that we

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:10.000
like people to deal with

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:12.000
so I used to work with

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:14.000
engineers a lot and some of the

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:16.000
sharpest and most functional engineers I worked with

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:18.000
were called systems engineers

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
so like you think about your phone

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
and there is a whole engineering crew at Apple

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
or the people that make Android phones

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
that are battery engineers right

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
and they have engineers that work on the screen to optimize that

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.000
and the antenna and they have all these groups

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:32.000
of engineers and what a systems engineer does

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:34.000
is make sure all that stuff works together

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:36.000
that one thing is not taking too much

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.000
power so the other thing can't

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:40.000
work and so on. They just make it all happen

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.000
not at the end but along the way

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:44.000
and I feel like I realized maybe like a week

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:46.000
or two ago that my professional

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
life mostly has been spent

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
as what I would think of as a systems statistician

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.000
because we have a lot of packages that do

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:54.000
really interesting things and we want to use them

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:56.000
but they are not necessarily made to be consumed

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:58.000
to be used somewhere else

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:00.000
or in a different context than the

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
original author intended

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
so that is a lot of what we do

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.000
that is a lot of what I've been doing

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.000
and that is absolutely the goal of tiny models

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.000
so our job is to

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.000
really make our less frustrating

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
but really

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:16.000
it's really not that bad

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:18.000
it's very functional and with a few

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:20.000
extra tools you can get very very far

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:22.000
and build very effective models

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:24.000
and I stay here like

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:26.000
we usually talk about predictive models and machine learning

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
tiny models

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.000
can do pretty much everything

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:32.000
we have packages for hierarchical models

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.000
now survival models

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
and so on

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.000
so it's not just like a machine learning

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.000
library

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:42.000
so you've probably heard of the

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.000
tidyverse, I know that's kind of a ridiculous thing to say

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.000
but I've done this presentation where people

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:48.000
looked at me funny

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.000
and the tidyverse is built to have packages

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
that work really well together

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:54.000
to have a common sort of design goal

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:56.000
the naming is very similar

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:58.000
and it's very very thought out in how you

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.000
interface with the software

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:02.000
and anything else I've ever seen

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.000
and when Hadley first started working on that

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.000
he had these goals

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:08.000
that are listed here

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:10.000
don't make a new data structure that somebody has to learn

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.000
try to stick with data frames if you can

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:14.000
probably the most important

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.000
one here is design for humans

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:18.000
can anybody, raise your hand

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.000
if you know the function name

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
if you have a matrix and you want to

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.000
invert it, does anybody know what the function name is?

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.000
you first

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.000
solve

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.000
there's no inverse function

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:34.000
that's not designing for humans

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:36.000
so

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:38.000
it's those kind of things, we want to make things obvious

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:40.000
for you, we don't want you to get

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:42.000
a result back and be surprised

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:44.000
wait, why is it in a list and not in a data frame

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:46.000
that kind of thing, so when we think

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
about designing for humans in terms of

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.000
modeling, it's a little bit different from what they do

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:52.000
in the tidyverse

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:54.000
but at the end of the day

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:56.000
we want you to enjoy programming

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:58.000
and not be constantly frustrated by it

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.000
so

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
in some of the things that we do is we try to name

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.000
things and optimize them for auto

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.000
complete, so if you're doing model

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:08.000
tuning, all of our function names

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.000
that do that start with tune underbar

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.000
and then if you're in RStudio or VSCode

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.000
you can just tab and then you get the whole

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
list of things, whether they're

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:18.000
grids or tune objects or

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:20.000
things you can extract, like we try

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:22.000
to make function names as consistent as possible

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.000
Hannah

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:26.000
and when I don't

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:28.000
they fix it

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:30.000
so the other idea is this notion

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:32.000
of tidy data

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:34.000
there's a link here to when I

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:36.000
have these papers that really every

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.000
variable should be in a column, every row

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:40.000
or every observation

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.000
forms a row, that's a little bit weird for us sometimes

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.000
because sometimes we have

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:46.000
records that

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:48.000
have multiple sub-records

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.000
so if you're a patient

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:52.000
in a clinical trial or you're being followed longitudinally

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
the patient is really

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:56.000
the observation, they're like the independent

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.000
experimental unit and they might have

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:00.000
multiple rows in the data set

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:02.000
so some of this we have to deal with a little bit

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:04.000
but our

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:06.000
idea is we want to create

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:08.000
modeling packages that work well together

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:10.000
that do a lot of things and that

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:12.000
you know when you start using them, even if

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:14.000
you haven't used the other parts of it, you'll

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.000
already know what to expect when you get there

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.000
so I've been thinking about

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.000
modeling for a long time and if you

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.000
look at the tutorial

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:24.000
I mentioned that in

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:26.000
the process of having a career doing

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:28.000
modeling before coming to our

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:30.000
deposit

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:32.000
you can edit that out, right?

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:36.000
There were mistakes were made

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:38.000
you learn a lot along the way

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:40.000
and so a lot of that informs how we

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.000
design our software

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:44.000
so the first bullet point there

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.000
is type equal prop, that's

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.000
just remember that one, right? So when you use

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:50.000
our code we'll make the translation for you

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:52.000
for whether it's probability

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.000
or posterior or whatever

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.000
if you want to use the form method or not the form method

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.000
we'll handle that for you so we don't want you to have

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:00.000
to worry about that. Another

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:02.000
thing that's important to me over the year

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:04.000
is resampling and empirical validation

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:06.000
that when you have

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:08.000
a model and you want to know

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.000
if you want to get something out of it you should be able to

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.000
quantify its performance

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:14.000
hopefully using something like cross-validation

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:16.000
of the bootstrap. I've sat in a lot

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:18.000
of presentations where people present

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:20.000
results with logistic regression

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:22.000
and how important it is that this

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:24.000
p-value is for the interaction

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:26.000
is less than .05 and then

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:28.000
you ask what the accuracy of the model is and it's like

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:30.000
60% and you're like, okay

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:32.000
so there's a lot more to

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:34.000
qualifying and validating

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:36.000
your model beyond just doing predictive modeling

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
Another thing that we

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.000
do in tiny models is

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:42.000
it's designed with some hidden guardrails

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:44.000
at least in machine learning a lot of the problems

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:46.000
that occur that you don't necessarily know

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:48.000
happen until you get new data

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:50.000
those are the result of people using maybe the wrong

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.000
data at the wrong time for the wrong thing

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.000
or using it for multiple things

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.000
and so we

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:58.000
sort of, you sort of have to go out of

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:00.000
your way in tiny models to sort of use the

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.000
data inappropriately by accident

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:04.000
and so we want

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:06.000
people to also be able to use the infrastructure

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:08.000
to make your own packages pretty easily

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:10.000
and we want to encourage people to do things

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:12.000
that they necessarily couldn't

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:14.000
because I've heard a lot of people say

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:16.000
yeah, that is probably a better way to do this

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.000
but I don't know how to use that software

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:20.000
or I don't have a license for that or

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:22.000
it's not been written and I'm probably not going to

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:24.000
write it. So we want to also sort of

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:26.000
like the next slide has the phrase

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:28.000
leveling up. Does everyone know what that means?

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:30.000
It means like how can I improve me

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:32.000
or my tool set to get

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:34.000
more out of what I'm doing

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:36.000
and just some examples of that is

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:38.000
a lot of times we have variables

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:40.000
like predictors in our data and

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:42.000
we use a model that can't handle them

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:44.000
as character data, you know, because they're categories

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:46.000
and so we have to convert them

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:48.000
to indicator variables

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:50.000
there are a lot of different ways you can do that

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:52.000
and a lot of times there haven't been

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:54.000
there have been methodologies

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:56.000
out there that people just didn't have available

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:58.000
to them or the package wasn't easy

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:00.000
to use and so on. So

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:02.000
just as examples, there are things

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:04.000
called effect encoding methods that can be

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:06.000
very effective in certain situations

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.000
feature hashing is an excellent

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:10.000
tool if you have like

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:12.000
categories that have maybe

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:14.000
like thousands or millions of levels

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:16.000
and things like that. Also

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:18.000
multiple choice predictors. I've had

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:20.000
codes laying around in scripts for years

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:22.000
that take, you know, if I had a

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:24.000
model and a predictor was like what languages

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:26.000
do you speak, you know, some person

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:28.000
might have one, somebody might have four

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:30.000
and so having like a way

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:32.000
to deal with multiple categories is

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:34.000
really helpful. So we're trying to institutionalize

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:36.000
as much of that as we can in tiny models

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:38.000
so you can just use it and not have to

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:40.000
carry around your little bits

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:42.000
that you've been doing.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:44.000
I had these slides already written before I saw

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:46.000
Di's presentation but

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:48.000
also some modern dimension

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:50.000
reduction methods like

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:52.000
UMAP which he showed and

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:54.000
these fancy name things

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:56.000
like manifold based multi-dimensional

00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:58.000
scaling and things like that. So, you know

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:00.000
there are things we see in papers and all that

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:02.000
but we don't necessarily have the tools

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:04.000
to fit them and so we want you to try to

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:06.000
use them. Maybe they're not effective

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:08.000
maybe they are but having the

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:10.000
ability to even try that is important

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:12.000
to us. You know there's other

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:14.000
things like a lot of different imputation

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:16.000
tools are out there so we just want you to

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:18.000
be able to use this stuff.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:20.000
So, you know, if there's something like yeah

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:22.000
I use this all the time but I can't find it anywhere

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:24.000
just come to our repos and put an issue we'd like

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:26.000
to hear from you.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:28.000
Alright, so if you want to learn more besides this

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:30.000
there's three main resources.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:32.000
There's tinymodels.org. We spent a lot

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:34.000
of time on that during the very beginning of the

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:36.000
pandemic just sort of optimizing

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:38.000
that putting a lot of articles in there

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:40.000
searchable list of functions

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:42.000
a lot of really nice

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:44.000
sequential set of getting started

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:46.000
articles.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:48.000
Julius Hilge and I wrote

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:50.000
a book on tinymodels.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:52.000
You can get it from O'Reilly or you can just go to

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:54.000
this link and take a look at it. That's

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:56.000
very helpful if you want longer form

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:58.000
documentation. And also some of you

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:00.000
may know after the other day

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:02.000
we keep all of our training materials

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:04.000
in the same place. We keep all

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:06.000
the old versions so if we change data sets you

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:08.000
can always get to the version that you used

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:10.000
but you can go to workshops.tinymodels.org

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:12.000
and there's a lot of training materials there.

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:14.000
And all this is licensed in a

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:16.000
way that you can use it in your classes

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:18.000
or for whatever you need.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:20.000
Okay, so let's look at

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:22.000
some code maybe. Like the

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:24.000
tinyverse we have like a meta package.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:26.000
So if you load tinymodels you see this big

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:28.000
amount

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:30.000
of output you get back. We load

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:32.000
things like dplyr and ggplot which are

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:34.000
not part of tinymodels but you're probably going to want to use

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:36.000
those. And also

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:38.000
like tinyverse we list these

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:40.000
conflicts. You know things

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:42.000
like dplyr has a filter function

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:44.000
but the stats package has a filter function.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:46.000
If you just type filter

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:48.000
the one that you get is based on which

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:50.000
package was loaded more recently.

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:52.000
And so one thing that we added here

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:54.000
is this thing at the very bottom called

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:56.000
tinymodels prefer and what

00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:58.000
that does is it has

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:00.000
uses the package that Hadley wrote called

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:02.000
conflicted that manages these

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.000
conflicts. So after running this

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:06.000
function assuming you want

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:08.000
to use dplyr and tinymodels

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:10.000
it will sort of default your filter

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:12.000
no matter how it gets loaded

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:14.000
to use the dplyr one.

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:16.000
So you don't have to use this but if you're

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:18.000
sort of tired of dealing with these and have the wrong

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:20.000
function from the wrong package

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:22.000
this can be a

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:24.000
big help for you to resolve that.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:26.000
Alright

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:28.000
so I have some example data. It's a little bit

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:30.000
more than 10,000 data points

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:32.000
and it's something about

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:34.000
restaurant deliveries like food deliveries.

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:36.000
So basically we have

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:38.000
a time period from when the order was put

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:40.000
in to when it was delivered.

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:42.000
There's a few variables. There's the

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:44.000
order time is like the hour. You know 0 to

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:46.000
like 24.

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:48.000
There's a day of the week.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:50.000
So it's a factor. It's Monday,

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:52.000
Tuesday, Wednesday that kind of thing.

00:23:52.000 --> 00:23:54.000
There's distance and also

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:56.000
there's 27 pre-made sort of

00:23:56.000 --> 00:23:58.000
indicators and this is like the result

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:00.000
of like a multiple choice thing. These are

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:02.000
counts of the things that were ordered

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:04.000
so like item 3 might be somebody ordered

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:06.000
a nice tea or something like that.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:08.000
So we want to take this information and try to predict

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:10.000
how long it would take you or me to get

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:12.000
our food at home

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:14.000
or wherever it's being delivered to.

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:16.000
So it's a fairly decent sized

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:18.000
data. It's 10,000 data points. There's not

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:20.000
that many variables.

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:22.000
The first thing we'll do is we'll look at the outcome.

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:24.000
I should say if anybody

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:26.000
here does survival analysis you're probably

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:28.000
wondering if any of this data is censored.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:30.000
This is all complete data. Censored means

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:32.000
if I put an order in

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:34.000
and it's five minutes after

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:36.000
I don't know when it's going to get here so I don't know the

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:38.000
actual delivery time but I know it's at

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:40.000
least five minutes. And so these are all

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:42.000
complete values where

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:44.000
they've actually had the delivery and they know what the time

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:46.000
was. And you can see it's right skewed

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:48.000
which is pretty common with

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:50.000
time data. It's non-zero.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:52.000
It ranges from maybe like

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:54.000
12 to

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:56.000
around 60. It's right skewed

00:24:56.000 --> 00:24:58.000
with a little bit of a mode here.

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:00.000
So one of the things we might

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:02.000
think about is do we

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:04.000
do anything special about this?

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:06.000
One thing you might think about doing is logging

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:08.000
the outcome and then doing that.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:10.000
I'm just going to keep the outcome the way it is.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:12.000
And the only other thing I'm going to

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:14.000
do with it special

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:16.000
is I'm going to split the data up.

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:18.000
I'm going to split it into a training set,

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:20.000
a test set, and a validation set.

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:22.000
And the validation set is sort of like

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:24.000
a test set but you can use it along the way to

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:26.000
figure out how well your model is using

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:28.000
or how well it's working.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:30.000
The test set is really at the very, very end

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:32.000
when you want to just validate

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:34.000
what your results were. So when

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:36.000
I do that split, what I don't want to happen is

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:38.000
I don't want to have, you know, all

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:40.000
of these sort of like outlying extreme

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:42.000
data points end up accidentally in the test

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:44.000
or the training set. So when I

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:46.000
use this function in TidyMiles called initial

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:48.000
validation split, it'll put

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:50.000
60% in the training set, 20%

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:52.000
in validation, and the remaining 20%

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:54.000
in testing. And what it'll do

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:56.000
is it'll do that three-way split

00:25:56.000 --> 00:25:58.000
by

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:00.000
chopping this distribution up into

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:02.000
quartiles and doing the split

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:04.000
in each quartile of the data and then

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:06.000
recombining them together. So the

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:08.000
distribution of this outcome and

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:10.000
all three of those data sets should be very, very

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:12.000
similar to one another. So we can make sure

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:14.000
by doing that, we can make sure the distribution

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:16.000
here looks the same across the training

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:18.000
set, the test set, and the validation set.

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:20.000
So in the code

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:22.000
here, you know, we get to split about

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:24.000
6,000 data points for model fitting,

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:26.000
about 2,000 for validation,

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:28.000
and about 2,000 for testing.

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:30.000
We try to make our function

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:32.000
names as obvious as possible.

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:34.000
So if you have the

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:36.000
object that has the

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:38.000
information about the splitting, you want to get the training set

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:40.000
out, we're going to name that training for you.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:42.000
And validation is the function

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:44.000
that brings back the validation set.

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:46.000
So, you know, this takes a split and you get

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:48.000
a data frame out of here with the appropriate

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:50.000
6,004 rows

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:52.000
and so on. Now a lot of

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:54.000
times I talk about resampling, like

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:56.000
cross-validation, the bootstrap, and those

00:26:56.000 --> 00:26:58.000
are ways to use your training set

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:00.000
to get good estimates of performance that are not

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:02.000
overly optimistic. And I'm not going to

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:04.000
be doing cross-validation or resampling

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:06.000
or the bootstrap or

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:08.000
something like that. I'm going to use my validation set

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:10.000
sort of as like a single resample.

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:12.000
And to put that sort of into the tiny model format

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:14.000
the same way you would get

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:16.000
the same format as cross-validation,

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:18.000
do a little extra step here and take that split

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:20.000
object and pull out the validation

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:22.000
set in a way that we can consume

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:24.000
this by some of the functions

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:26.000
we'll use later.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:30.000
So, you know, I think

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:32.000
I see this on one of the slides upcoming

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:34.000
is one of my college professors

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:36.000
said that the only way to be

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:38.000
comfortable with your data is to never look at it.

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:40.000
And so, you know, when you look

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:42.000
at this data a little bit, you look at

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:44.000
the time of the order, and clearly

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:46.000
the delivery time increases with that

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:48.000
and it's maybe not linear. So

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:50.000
this is something, if we're going to fit like a linear regression

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:52.000
here, we need to think about

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:54.000
that there's a non-linear effect here.

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:56.000
I use geomSmooth,

00:27:56.000 --> 00:27:58.000
and what geomSmooth does under the hood is that

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:00.000
you use something called a spline function.

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:02.000
And what a spline does is it takes the original

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:04.000
time variable and sort of expands it

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:06.000
to these kind of weird extra

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:08.000
columns, and those extra columns

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:10.000
are the ones that are used in the linear regression.

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:12.000
So this smooth line

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:14.000
here that you see here is the prediction

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:16.000
from like a linear model that uses

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:18.000
maybe five or ten of these extra

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:20.000
non-linear terms based on the

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:22.000
order time.

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:24.000
That'll be relevant in a minute, so that's why I'm

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:26.000
lecturing on geomSmooth.

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:28.000
But this is something we need to think about if we're

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:30.000
going to fit like a linear model.

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:32.000
But if you look at it a little more closely, it's actually

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:34.000
a lot more complicated because it turns

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:36.000
out if you look at that

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:38.000
same trend and estimate

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:40.000
it differently for the day of the week the order was made,

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:42.000
it's quite different, that

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:44.000
Friday and Saturday have a very,

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:46.000
very steep non-linear curve, whereas

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:48.000
something like Monday is a lot more

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:50.000
blunted. So if we

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:52.000
just did this and put it in the model, we're going to

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:54.000
underfit because it actually

00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:56.000
depends. And that's

00:28:56.000 --> 00:28:58.000
what a statistical interaction is, is when you have

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:00.000
two predictors and their relationship

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:02.000
with the outcome, they depend on one another.

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:04.000
So in this case, just knowing the day of the week

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:06.000
is not enough, and it's also not

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:08.000
good enough to just do this non-linear function

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:10.000
of time. You have to sort of

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:12.000
consider them together, and so we'll do that in just a minute.

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:16.000
All right, so

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:18.000
we have this amazing patch code recipes,

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:20.000
and what it does is it prepares your data

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:22.000
for modeling. And you can start off

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:24.000
by just giving it any data set,

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:26.000
but we'll use the training set here.

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:28.000
And we'll use a formula, and all it

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:30.000
really does is, what the formula does

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:32.000
is it says, things on the left side

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:34.000
of the utility are outcomes

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:36.000
and everything else represented by

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:38.000
the dot is a predictor. So at this stage

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:40.000
all the recipe does is says, okay, what's the

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:42.000
role? Is it a predictor, is it an outcome?

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:44.000
And it looks at the actual columns, and it measures

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:46.000
like, are they category, are they

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:48.000
factor, or strings, or

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:50.000
ordered, or numeric, or integer. So it sort of

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:52.000
just investigates the data

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:54.000
and remembers what the

00:29:54.000 --> 00:29:56.000
columns are. Now the way

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:58.000
recipes works is it's a little bit like

00:29:58.000 --> 00:30:00.000
the formula method or model.matrix

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:02.000
in R, but with a flavor

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:04.000
of like dplyr. In dplyr, you would

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:06.000
keep piping in things that you want to do to the

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:08.000
data until you have it the way you want it.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:10.000
And the recipe works the same way. We're going to

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:12.000
pipe in declarations

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:14.000
of like, hey, I want you to log the data

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:16.000
now, and I want you to do this with the data.

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:18.000
So the first thing we'll do

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:20.000
is we'll create indicator variables

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:22.000
for the day of the week

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:24.000
by using a function

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:26.000
called stepdummy. So those indicator variables

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:28.000
are sometimes called dummy variables.

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:30.000
So we're not mad at this variable.

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:32.000
It's just like stepdummy is the name of it.

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:34.000
And so all these things we're going to do and

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:36.000
pipe in, they're called step functions. They all

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:38.000
start with step under bar. And then

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:40.000
the first argument in all of them is

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:42.000
what variable should be affected by this.

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:44.000
And you can use any dplyr selector here like

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:46.000
you would with select. You could put in

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:48.000
like everything minus something

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:50.000
and starts with

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:52.000
or whatever you want. But at

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:54.000
this point, what you're saying is I want you to

00:30:54.000 --> 00:30:56.000
take this column, make indicator

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:58.000
variables out of it, then take it out

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:00.000
and then leave the resulting indicators

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:02.000
in there. There's a lot

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:04.000
more you can do besides the dummy variables.

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:06.000
Take a look at this chapter in the

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:08.000
Tiny Models book. It's something

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:10.000
that we're very strong in for

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:12.000
this package. Oh, and one thing

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:14.000
is, don't you hate

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:16.000
what BaseR does? In this case, it would

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:18.000
say like order day and then just

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:20.000
take the level and just jam it up next to it.

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:22.000
It's like the worst aesthetically thing

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:24.000
ever. So what we do in StepDummy

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:26.000
is you get to choose the delimiter and by default

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:28.000
it's under bar. So

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:30.000
the resulting Friday indicator would be

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:32.000
order day under bar FRI.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:34.000
So you have some control about how

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:36.000
it looks in your model results too.

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:38.000
Alright, remember that though, that it's going to

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:40.000
be named that.

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:42.000
What you could have done is recipes

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:44.000
have a bunch, like a lot

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:46.000
of extra selectors that you can just use

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:48.000
here. And you can choose variables not

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:50.000
only by their type, like are they character

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:52.000
or factor or things like that, you can also

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:54.000
choose them by their role. So if you want to

00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:56.000
do something to all the predictors, whatever

00:31:56.000 --> 00:31:58.000
might be in there, you can just say

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:00.000
all predictors instead of listing them all

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:02.000
out. And so there's

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:04.000
just a lot here that you can do with, and

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:06.000
it's kind of a strong

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:08.000
thing that we like about this because

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:10.000
generally speaking, there are some recipe steps

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:12.000
that will get rid of variables. So if

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:14.000
you start writing specific variables down, especially

00:32:14.000 --> 00:32:16.000
late in the recipe, you may have

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:18.000
eliminated them and it might cause an error in the

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:20.000
recipe because you're saying, do this to variable x

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:22.000
but variable x isn't in the data anymore.

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:24.000
So we encourage people to use

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:26.000
very generic

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:28.000
selectors here.

00:32:28.000 --> 00:32:30.000
Alright, so what's next?

00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:32.000
We have a lot of

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:34.000
indicator variables, I think I

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:36.000
call them item, and there are counts.

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:38.000
But there might be one of those items in the

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:40.000
training set where it just

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:42.000
so happened they almost

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:44.000
never get ordered, and the training set

00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:46.000
might have all zeros in it. That's not

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:48.000
a big deal for some models, but for other models

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:50.000
it doesn't like having a column of all zeros.

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:52.000
So we call that a zero variance predictor.

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:54.000
So what this would do is when you

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:56.000
use this recipe, it would look at your training set

00:32:56.000 --> 00:32:58.000
it would find any of the predictors

00:32:58.000 --> 00:33:00.000
I used all predictors, so

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:02.000
it would search those and look for anything that has

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:04.000
any column that has one

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:06.000
unique value, and it marks that as

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:08.000
you should get rid of that. And so this

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:10.000
is a little helpful thing you can do.

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:12.000
We also have something for what

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:14.000
we call near zero variance predictors.

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:16.000
Imagine you have like a thousand rows

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:18.000
and you have 999 zeros

00:33:18.000 --> 00:33:20.000
in a single one, right?

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:22.000
That's maybe not what you want in your data set. So we have

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:24.000
some other ways of doing this that are a little more general.

00:33:24.000 --> 00:33:26.000
Alright.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:28.000
So then what we're going to do is

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:30.000
we're going to do splines. We're going to do

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:32.000
exactly what GM smooth does.

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:34.000
We're going to take our original column of

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:36.000
the hour that the order came in,

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:38.000
and we're going to generate as many columns

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:40.000
as we want to make it non-linear.

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:42.000
And if we add 100 columns

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:44.000
it's going to be a really wiggly line.

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:46.000
If we add very few columns, like 2 or 3,

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:48.000
it's going to be a relatively smooth line.

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:50.000
And so, you know, we don't know how many to add.

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:52.000
The typical

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:54.000
parameter for that is called the degrees of freedom

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:56.000
of the spline. And I'm just going to add

00:33:56.000 --> 00:33:58.000
5 columns to represent that

00:33:58.000 --> 00:34:00.000
non-linearly. Why 5?

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:02.000
I just picked it out of the air.

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:04.000
It's not, I mean, looking at this,

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:06.000
it's not like a super wiggly

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:08.000
point here, or a relationship.

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:10.000
5, I'd probably do fine.

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:12.000
But we have a variety

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:14.000
of other basis expansions. There's a lot

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:16.000
of different ways you can do splines. There's polynomial

00:34:16.000 --> 00:34:18.000
expansions. So there's quite a lot of ways you

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:20.000
can represent a column

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:22.000
in a non-linear way to the model you're

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:24.000
going to use. But you might not, you might

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:26.000
be saying, like, I don't know about 5, though. I'm kind

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:28.000
of stuck on that. You don't have

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:30.000
to actually pick it.

00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:32.000
You'll see later that you can actually tune these

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:34.000
options. So I can give it a

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:36.000
non-value of this

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:38.000
function called tune. And all that does

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:40.000
is it just marks it to say, like,

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:42.000
hey, later on, I don't, you're not going to be able to

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:44.000
do this recipe until you know what this is.

00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:46.000
But we'll do it in a way that

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:48.000
we'll search over different values of that

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:50.000
parameter to figure out what the best performance is.

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:52.000
So you can mark pretty much

00:34:52.000 --> 00:34:54.000
anything in here as being tunable

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:56.000
and then just optimize it

00:34:56.000 --> 00:34:58.000
however you want to.

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:00.000
So, here we are.

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:02.000
We have, remember we have dummy

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:04.000
variables that are, like, order day

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:06.000
in the factor level. When

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:08.000
we make spline terms, the way they're going to

00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:10.000
be named is they're going to be, like, order time

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:12.000
under bar 1, under bar

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:14.000
2, under bar, all the way up to 5.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:16.000
So if you want to add interactions,

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:18.000
and I looked to see if you can do this in BaseR,

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:20.000
and you kind of can.

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:22.000
You can make interactions between a factor

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:24.000
and a spline expansion, but you can only do it

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:26.000
for one variable because it gives the

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:28.000
splines the same names if you did it with a second

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:30.000
variable. So we can

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:32.000
do it for one variable. We can do it for

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:34.000
pretty much everything, and the way we would

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:36.000
do that is something called step interact,

00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:38.000
and then you can just give it whatever interactions

00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:40.000
you want to, and those interactions could

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:42.000
use starts with or any dplyr selector.

00:35:42.000 --> 00:35:44.000
So we know all our indicators start

00:35:44.000 --> 00:35:46.000
with order day. We know our spline

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:48.000
terms start off with order time,

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:50.000
and that will let our spline

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:52.000
terms, those relationships

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:54.000
be different for day of the week,

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:56.000
which it looks like they are.

00:35:56.000 --> 00:35:58.000
So this is something that would be a little bit

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:00.000
hard to do with BaseR, but

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:02.000
it's actually pretty simple to do it this way.

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:04.000
Alright, and then

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:06.000
the last thing we'll do is, just for kicks,

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:08.000
just to show that you can do it, is

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:10.000
there are some models like GlimNet or

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:12.000
k-nearest neighbors or something like that, where

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:14.000
if you don't, they're going

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:16.000
to want all the variables in the same units.

00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:18.000
If you think

00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:20.000
about computing a distance, if something

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:22.000
is in square meters

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:24.000
and another thing is in

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:26.000
low counts like 0, 1, 2, 3,

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:28.000
those aren't in the same units, and

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:30.000
the variable with the larger numbers

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:32.000
is going to dominate the computations.

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:34.000
So what StepNormalize does

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:36.000
is with your training set, it estimates

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:38.000
the mean and variance of every column,

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:40.000
and then when it goes to process

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:42.000
the data set with the recipe, it subtracts

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:44.000
the mean and divides by standard deviation,

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:46.000
so everything has a standard

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:48.000
normal distribution. And we're going to use GlimNet

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:50.000
in a minute, so, spoiler alert,

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:52.000
we need to do this for it.

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:54.000
Alright, so this is the things

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:56.000
we do to our data before we put it in the model,

00:36:56.000 --> 00:36:58.000
and then how we make the model in TinyModels.

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:00.000
So what we do is

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:02.000
the package that does that

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:04.000
is called Parsnip. Parsnip

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:06.000
has different model functions.

00:37:06.000 --> 00:37:08.000
So it's sort of almost like a two or three step

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:10.000
process here, is you say what model you want to use.

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:12.000
So the first thing you do is you say

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:14.000
I want to use linear regression.

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:16.000
And all that says is my outcome

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:18.000
is a number, and my predictor

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:20.000
should be like slopes and intercepts.

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:22.000
That's pretty much all it says. It doesn't say how you're

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:24.000
going to do the estimation, it doesn't say

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:26.000
what those values should be or what not.

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:28.000
There's different modeling

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:30.000
functions, so like

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:32.000
nearest neighbor model is very

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:34.000
equation-wise, like very different than linear

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:36.000
regression. There's model functions

00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:38.000
for random forest, for decision trees,

00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:40.000
there's a whole host of them for time series models

00:37:40.000 --> 00:37:42.000
and so on. So step one

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:44.000
with TinyModels is tell me what you

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:46.000
want to do. Like what is it that you want

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:48.000
the end result to be? And then the second thing

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:50.000
you say is well how should I do it?

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:52.000
And the how that we do it is called

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:54.000
the engine. And so the default

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:56.000
engine for linear regression is LM, but I'm

00:37:56.000 --> 00:37:58.000
going to show it here. You would just

00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:00.000
pipe into that linear regression

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:02.000
function, set my engine to be LM.

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:04.000
And, you know, we could do that

00:38:04.000 --> 00:38:06.000
but, you know, maybe not. We could

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:08.000
also use like TensorFlow.

00:38:08.000 --> 00:38:10.000
So maybe you want to use some sort of weird objective function

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:12.000
through TensorFlow where you have a lot of data and you want

00:38:12.000 --> 00:38:14.000
to batch it. You can do that too.

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:16.000
Or if you're more of a torch person, we have a

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:18.000
torch modeling package called Brule.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:20.000
You could do that. If you have

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:22.000
a lot of data, maybe you want to use Spark.

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:24.000
You might have your data in a Spark cluster.

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:26.000
So you can fit that model using Spark.

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:28.000
If you're like me

00:38:28.000 --> 00:38:30.000
and you're really into Bayesian models,

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:32.000
you can fit a linear regression

00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:34.000
using Stan. So that's not doing maximum

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:36.000
likelihood, it's doing like Bayesian

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:38.000
estimation using priors and all that

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:40.000
stuff. The thing we're

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:42.000
going to use is GlimNet. And GlimNet's a really

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:44.000
nice model. The package will be a little

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:46.000
bit frustrating, but it's an excellent model

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:48.000
that can handle a lot of different things.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:50.000
It automatically does feature selection for you

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:52.000
and has a lot of niceties to it.

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:54.000
So we've set our engine.

00:38:54.000 --> 00:38:56.000
We're ready to go.

00:38:56.000 --> 00:38:58.000
It does have some tuning parameters.

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:00.000
And these tuning parameters are things that you need to set

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:02.000
up front. You can't directly

00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:04.000
estimate them like you estimate slopes and intercepts.

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:06.000
You have to say up front what they should be. Sort of like

00:39:06.000 --> 00:39:08.000
the degrees of freedom. It's something that matters

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:10.000
a lot, but there's no equation that tells you what

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:12.000
the value should be. And the first one there

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:14.000
is called the penalty. So GlimNet

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:16.000
is a regularization method. It penalizes

00:39:16.000 --> 00:39:18.000
your coefficients. And so

00:39:18.000 --> 00:39:20.000
usually that penalty is between 0 and, I don't know, like

00:39:20.000 --> 00:39:22.000
1. So I'm going to just pick

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:24.000
.1 here just to show it to you.

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:26.000
And then GlimNet can also penalize

00:39:26.000 --> 00:39:28.000
in two different ways. It can do something called ridge regression.

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:30.000
And it can also do something called

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:32.000
lasso regression. Or it can do some

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:34.000
mixture of the two of them. And so

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:36.000
by saying mixture equal .5 here,

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:38.000
I'm going to say give me a 50-50 mix

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:40.000
of the ridge penalty

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:42.000
and a 50-50 mix of the lasso penalty.

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:44.000
And so these are just things that

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:46.000
you would have to figure out which one worked better

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:48.000
and which ones don't.

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:50.000
And also if you've ever used GlimNet or

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:52.000
seen it, we're avoiding

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:54.000
a lot of jargon here. Because in GlimNet

00:39:54.000 --> 00:39:56.000
they call these lambda and alpha.

00:39:56.000 --> 00:39:58.000
And so unless you're like

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:00.000
reading up on the statistical literature

00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:02.000
in the original papers, like the help

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:04.000
file tells you that. But if you look at the function

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:06.000
definition and it's lambda, it's like, what is

00:40:06.000 --> 00:40:08.000
that? So we try to, as much as

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:10.000
possible, avoid jargon. Whether that's

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:12.000
a Greek letter or something

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:14.000
that's just really specific to that package.

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:16.000
We try to keep all the names the same

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:18.000
of arguments and try to avoid

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:20.000
sort of like things that maybe people wouldn't

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:22.000
know what they are by looking at them.

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:24.000
Alright. So we know

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:26.000
what we want to do and how we want to do it.

00:40:26.000 --> 00:40:28.000
So let's actually do it. Now we

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:30.000
have a recipe that's going to

00:40:30.000 --> 00:40:32.000
process our data and give it in a format

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:34.000
that we want to GlimNet. And so we

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:36.000
can do that in like a couple steps.

00:40:36.000 --> 00:40:38.000
But the best and probably most straightforward

00:40:38.000 --> 00:40:40.000
thing you can do is combine them together

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:42.000
in something called a workflow.

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:44.000
And if you've ever seen like a Scikit-learn pipeline,

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:46.000
it's basically the same thing. We're basically

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:48.000
binding a preprocessor, which is

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:50.000
the recipe, to a model and use

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:52.000
them as one unit. So by

00:40:52.000 --> 00:40:54.000
adding the model and adding the workflow

00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:56.000
or adding the recipe into this workflow,

00:40:56.000 --> 00:40:58.000
I can do everything with this one object.

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:00.000
So if I want to fit my training set

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:02.000
to fit my model to the

00:41:02.000 --> 00:41:04.000
training set, if you just

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:06.000
use this with the workflow,

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:08.000
it processes the recipe the way it's supposed

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:10.000
to. It knows what the predictors

00:41:10.000 --> 00:41:12.000
are. It knows what the outcome is. It knows how to hand

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:14.000
it off to the modeling function. And then

00:41:14.000 --> 00:41:16.000
the modeling function knows, oh yeah,

00:41:16.000 --> 00:41:18.000
GlimNet needs a matrix, so we're going to make

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:20.000
sure we give it a matrix and does all the things

00:41:20.000 --> 00:41:22.000
that GlimNet needs. And then

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:24.000
just as easily, the predict method is

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:26.000
one simple step.

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:28.000
We're just predicting the first five rows

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:30.000
of the validation set here. And you can

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:32.000
see it comes back as a table.

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:34.000
Most modeling functions will give you back

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:36.000
a vector unless you're doing multivariate,

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:38.000
in which case it's probably a matrix, or if you're

00:41:38.000 --> 00:41:40.000
doing classifications, sometimes it's a vector,

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:42.000
but sometimes it's a matrix if you're getting probabilities.

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:44.000
And the point I'm getting at here

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:46.000
is we want everything in data frames,

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:48.000
even if it's a data frame with a single row.

00:41:48.000 --> 00:41:50.000
Because you can very easily just

00:41:50.000 --> 00:41:52.000
bind calls this to your

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:54.000
original data. You can

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:56.000
do a lot more with a data frame

00:41:56.000 --> 00:41:58.000
if you're into the tidyverse,

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:00.000
than you have getting output out. You don't know

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:02.000
if it's going to be a vector or a matrix or a data frame.

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:04.000
So we always do everything with

00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:06.000
data frames, and the naming of these things is

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:08.000
very consistent. So you'll always know the

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:10.000
names of what you get out.

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:12.000
Now, what I can do now is if

00:42:12.000 --> 00:42:14.000
I want to see if this model works well in the validation

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:16.000
set, I can predict the entire validation

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:18.000
set, C-bind that

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:20.000
to my original data where the outcome is,

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:22.000
and then I can look at one of the

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:24.000
tiny models functions that computes the root

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:26.000
mean squared error, and do all that.

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:28.000
But we don't want you to have to worry about that.

00:42:28.000 --> 00:42:30.000
We have a function, a suite

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:32.000
of functions that do that.

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:34.000
So using validation is like a single

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:36.000
resample. So the code that you see here

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:38.000
is the same code that you would use if you're using

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:40.000
cross-validation or time series resampling.

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:42.000
What you do is, basically,

00:42:42.000 --> 00:42:44.000
it's called fit resample. So we have a single

00:42:44.000 --> 00:42:46.000
one, and you just give it your

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:48.000
resampling object, which we defined

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:50.000
early on, and the workflow.

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:52.000
And then it'll just

00:42:52.000 --> 00:42:54.000
fit, whether it's 10 models for

00:42:54.000 --> 00:42:56.000
10-fold cross-validation, it's just one

00:42:56.000 --> 00:42:58.000
for this validation set. It'll do that

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:00.000
for every tuning parameter

00:43:00.000 --> 00:43:02.000
value you have. We only have one right now.

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:04.000
And then get the predictions

00:43:04.000 --> 00:43:06.000
and the right data, compute the

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:08.000
performance metrics, and give those back to you.

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:10.000
So by running these three lines

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:12.000
of code, you get an object back,

00:43:12.000 --> 00:43:14.000
and if you want to get the performance metrics

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:16.000
out of it, you can see here the

00:43:16.000 --> 00:43:18.000
two that come back automatically. The root

00:43:18.000 --> 00:43:20.000
mean squared here is about 2.3

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:22.000
minutes, and the R squared is about 88%,

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:24.000
which is not bad, right? You might be like,

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:26.000
wow, that's pretty good, right?

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:28.000
But as I said,

00:43:28.000 --> 00:43:30.000
the only way to be comfortable with your data is to never

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:32.000
look at it. So we've also

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:34.000
developed a bunch of calibration

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:36.000
and diagnostic functions for a lot

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:38.000
of models in this package called probably.

00:43:38.000 --> 00:43:40.000
So if I load the probably

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:42.000
package, there's a function called

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:44.000
calplot

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:46.000
regression. There's a bunch of calplot

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:48.000
methods, and that just does the

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:50.000
observe versus predicted, and

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:52.000
keeps the axes the

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:54.000
same, and

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:56.000
aspect ratio of one die,

00:43:56.000 --> 00:43:58.000
and then it puts a little smoother on

00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:00.000
there, and you can see that actually the fits are

00:44:00.000 --> 00:44:02.000
pretty good, unless you're

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:04.000
really going to take more than 40 minutes, and then we're

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:06.000
really, really under predicting the data.

00:44:06.000 --> 00:44:08.000
So that R squared of 88% might look

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:10.000
pretty great, but maybe not

00:44:10.000 --> 00:44:12.000
once you look at this. So you might want

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:14.000
to add some more features, and you might try a

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:16.000
different model to figure out how you can

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:18.000
do better on this.

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:20.000
But the statistics don't always tell the entire

00:44:20.000 --> 00:44:22.000
story.

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:24.000
So what about parameters? I keep talking about tuning

00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:26.000
parameters. So at this point, I might say,

00:44:26.000 --> 00:44:28.000
well, maybe I need 10 degrees of freedom for the spline,

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:30.000
or maybe I should use a lower penalty or mixture.

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:32.000
At this point, what you can do is you can

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:34.000
mark all those things for tuning, and

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:36.000
then use our tuning machinery to

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:38.000
optimize those values

00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:40.000
to get the lowest root mean

00:44:40.000 --> 00:44:42.000
squared error. And we're going to do that, but we're

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:44.000
going to actually talk about a different model really quick.

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:46.000
I'm kind of running late, so I'm going to

00:44:46.000 --> 00:44:48.000
go through this a little bit. There's this amazing

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:50.000
model that not many people know about called Cubist,

00:44:50.000 --> 00:44:52.000
and it's been around for quite a long time,

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:54.000
and it's a little bit like a

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:56.000
boosted tree ensemble. What it

00:44:56.000 --> 00:44:58.000
initially does is it creates a regression

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:00.000
tree. In this case, I've made a really short

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:02.000
regression tree on this data set. You can see

00:45:02.000 --> 00:45:04.000
there's four terminal nodes. And what

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:06.000
a rule is, is it's a distinct path

00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:08.000
through this tree. So this is

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:10.000
a model with four rules in it.

00:45:10.000 --> 00:45:12.000
So what Cubist does is it gets these initial

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:14.000
rules, and then with each one of these

00:45:14.000 --> 00:45:16.000
data sets at the end, it fits a linear regression

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:18.000
to it. So now I have four

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:20.000
linear regressions from my model.

00:45:20.000 --> 00:45:22.000
And then, like boosting, it builds a sequence

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:24.000
of these models together, where

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:26.000
at the end of this ensembling process, you

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:28.000
might have 100 rules.

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:30.000
And you go to make a prediction. That prediction might

00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:32.000
only matter to like 20 of the rules.

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:34.000
It gets their linear regression predictions

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:36.000
and then it averages them. And it's a very, very

00:45:36.000 --> 00:45:38.000
effective model. And if you were wondering

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:40.000
what these rules look like, in this particular case,

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:42.000
here's a rule where the order time is

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:44.000
less than about 14 minutes,

00:45:44.000 --> 00:45:46.000
and if it was on a Friday or Saturday

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:48.000
and it was within, let's say, five miles,

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:50.000
then you should predict it using

00:45:50.000 --> 00:45:52.000
this model. Or if I had

00:45:52.000 --> 00:45:54.000
a longer running order,

00:45:54.000 --> 00:45:56.000
or, I'm sorry, it was later

00:45:56.000 --> 00:45:58.000
in the afternoon on a Saturday,

00:45:58.000 --> 00:46:00.000
you know, I think you should use this model

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:02.000
to predict. So in Cubist, you get

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:04.000
like maybe, you know, a subset

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:06.000
of the total rules for every prediction.

00:46:06.000 --> 00:46:08.000
It makes a bunch of linear regression predictions

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:10.000
and then it averages them together. And that tends

00:46:10.000 --> 00:46:12.000
to work pretty good. But we don't know how many

00:46:12.000 --> 00:46:14.000
things we should be averaging. We don't know if we should

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:16.000
just do a little or do a lot.

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:18.000
And so what we're going to do is tune that.

00:46:18.000 --> 00:46:20.000
So that model is available

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:22.000
in one of our packages called Rules, that has a bunch

00:46:22.000 --> 00:46:24.000
of rule-based models. It's called Cubist

00:46:24.000 --> 00:46:26.000
Rules. And then the variable

00:46:26.000 --> 00:46:28.000
that is the ensemble size is called

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:30.000
Committees. So I'll mark that for tuning.

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:32.000
You know, Cubist is easy.

00:46:32.000 --> 00:46:34.000
You don't have to do any indicator variables. You don't have to do

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:36.000
any transformations. You don't have to, I think

00:46:36.000 --> 00:46:38.000
it deals with missing values.

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:40.000
So I'm just going to give it, instead of a recipe,

00:46:40.000 --> 00:46:42.000
I'm going to have my workflow take a formula

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:44.000
and then

00:46:44.000 --> 00:46:46.000
go on my way. So I'm not going to tell

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:48.000
it how many committees to use. I'm going to say

00:46:48.000 --> 00:46:50.000
I want 25 of them, and you just pick

00:46:50.000 --> 00:46:52.000
ones based on everything you know about this

00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:54.000
variable, this tuning parameter.

00:46:54.000 --> 00:46:56.000
So instead of fitResamples, I'm

00:46:56.000 --> 00:46:58.000
going to use gridSearch, but the code is

00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:00.000
almost identical to what we did before.

00:47:00.000 --> 00:47:02.000
And it's going to use that validation set

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:04.000
and training set. It's going

00:47:04.000 --> 00:47:06.000
to do this for 25 different values of

00:47:06.000 --> 00:47:08.000
committees, measure performance using the

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:10.000
training set, and give you the metrics back.

00:47:10.000 --> 00:47:12.000
And when it does that, it looks like,

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:14.000
looking at it, it's like, oh, it wants a lot of

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:16.000
rules here, and the

00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:18.000
RMSE is,

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:20.000
you know, I'd probably say substantially lower,

00:47:20.000 --> 00:47:22.000
not massively lower, but it's an improvement

00:47:22.000 --> 00:47:24.000
on the linear regression model.

00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:26.000
I can auto-plot that

00:47:26.000 --> 00:47:28.000
and see what that trend is. Well, it turns

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:30.000
out that we don't actually need this many.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:32.000
We could probably do with like 10 or 12

00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:34.000
and get a simpler model and probably get

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:36.000
about the same level of performance.

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:38.000
So then, you know, so now I think I

00:47:38.000 --> 00:47:40.000
know what kind of qubis model I like.

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:42.000
You know, if you plot this, the data

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:44.000
points, you can see, oh, yeah, I like this better,

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:46.000
what not. Spoiler alert, this is a better model.

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:48.000
And then we have

00:47:48.000 --> 00:47:50.000
other machinery that I'm not going to go into too much

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:52.000
where you can finalize that model, say,

00:47:52.000 --> 00:47:54.000
oh, give me a qubis model with, you know,

00:47:54.000 --> 00:47:56.000
10 committees,

00:47:56.000 --> 00:47:58.000
and then we have a nice function called

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:00.000
last fit that it'll take that

00:48:00.000 --> 00:48:02.000
initial fit, it'll

00:48:02.000 --> 00:48:04.000
run the model on

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:06.000
your entire training set, fit the testing set,

00:48:06.000 --> 00:48:08.000
and give you the plot, the data for

00:48:08.000 --> 00:48:10.000
plotting the metrics in one easy step.

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:12.000
So that's like the gist

00:48:12.000 --> 00:48:14.000
of what TinyModels does.

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:16.000
I'm just trying to give you a flavor of like what the interface

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:18.000
looks like and the ways we think about this.

00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:20.000
If you're just doing something super simple

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:22.000
like, you know, empty

00:48:22.000 --> 00:48:24.000
cars, you know, you might just stick to

00:48:24.000 --> 00:48:26.000
LM and nobody here is going to be offended by that.

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:28.000
It's not for like I need something

00:48:28.000 --> 00:48:30.000
really complicated, but there are oftentimes

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:32.000
there's things you want to do that are just kind of a pain

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:34.000
in doing them in base R or in the

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:36.000
packages, so it's really designed to help with that a lot.

00:48:36.000 --> 00:48:38.000
So

00:48:38.000 --> 00:48:40.000
there's just some links here to things in the

00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:42.000
TinyModels book. I only have like

00:48:42.000 --> 00:48:44.000
two minutes.

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:46.000
The things that we've done recently is

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:48.000
hopefully before the end of the year we'll release

00:48:48.000 --> 00:48:50.000
all of the packages that have the

00:48:50.000 --> 00:48:52.000
integrated survival analysis, so

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:54.000
you can do everything we just talked about

00:48:54.000 --> 00:48:56.000
using like proportional hazards models or

00:48:56.000 --> 00:48:58.000
tree-based models for sensor data and so

00:48:58.000 --> 00:49:00.000
on. We spent a lot

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:02.000
of time, it turns out

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:04.000
case weights are really complicated

00:49:04.000 --> 00:49:06.000
and nobody really knew that

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:08.000
so we enabled that

00:49:08.000 --> 00:49:10.000
in a lot of places for TinyModels and

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:12.000
I just spent a lot of time decoding

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:14.000
what these things are called conformal

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:16.000
inference tools, so

00:49:16.000 --> 00:49:18.000
those are in probably. The things we're

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:20.000
working on right now is model

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:22.000
fairness metrics and ways to build

00:49:22.000 --> 00:49:24.000
your models to sort of mitigate any

00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:26.000
fairness issues.

00:49:26.000 --> 00:49:28.000
If anybody here does causal inference, we have some sort

00:49:28.000 --> 00:49:30.000
of prototype causal inference tools

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:32.000
so if you're interested, let us know. We'd love to get

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:34.000
you to look at those. And then

00:49:34.000 --> 00:49:36.000
one thing we want to do is post-processing.

00:49:36.000 --> 00:49:38.000
If you want to calibrate your

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:40.000
model or optimize

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:42.000
the probability threshold to

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:44.000
say whether something's an event or not

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:46.000
we have a list of things that we

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:48.000
want to allow you to do or even

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:50.000
optimize that come

00:49:50.000 --> 00:49:52.000
after the model fits. We have pre-processing

00:49:52.000 --> 00:49:54.000
the model, now we have a limited number

00:49:54.000 --> 00:49:56.000
of post-processing tools that we want to do.

00:49:56.000 --> 00:49:58.000
And then

00:49:58.000 --> 00:50:00.000
of course the most important thing, thank you

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:02.000
for the invitation to speak.

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:04.000
Everybody today was sharing their

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:06.000
mate with me. It was very nice.

00:50:06.000 --> 00:50:08.000
Word got around, I was like, take mine.

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:10.000
And especially thanks to the group.

00:50:10.000 --> 00:50:12.000
They do amazing work

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:14.000
including all the people who used to be in the group or

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:16.000
have been interns or helped out.

00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:18.000
It's been a huge team project

00:50:18.000 --> 00:50:20.000
and I really appreciate it.

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:22.000
Thanks.

00:50:22.000 --> 00:50:24.000
Questions?

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:40.000
Thank you for your

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:42.000
presentation.

00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:44.000
TidyMod is really

00:50:44.000 --> 00:50:46.000
big and I would like to know

00:50:46.000 --> 00:50:48.000
how, because in the process

00:50:48.000 --> 00:50:50.000
to do and compare

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:52.000
models you are doing a lot of

00:50:52.000 --> 00:50:54.000
steps and

00:50:54.000 --> 00:50:56.000
you have different randomness

00:50:56.000 --> 00:50:58.000
in some points and different

00:50:58.000 --> 00:51:00.000
the models also have some randomness

00:51:00.000 --> 00:51:02.000
inside and how you are

00:51:02.000 --> 00:51:04.000
thinking in the reproducibility

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:06.000
when you are comparing

00:51:06.000 --> 00:51:08.000
different models that have different

00:51:08.000 --> 00:51:10.000
levels of reproducibility

00:51:10.000 --> 00:51:12.000
there. I know that you have something

00:51:12.000 --> 00:51:14.000
saying about

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:16.000
here we have a problem

00:51:16.000 --> 00:51:18.000
about reproducibility but I don't

00:51:18.000 --> 00:51:20.000
remember where.

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:22.000
So the effect

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:24.000
of randomness on the models

00:51:24.000 --> 00:51:26.000
the first thing I would say is

00:51:26.000 --> 00:51:28.000
that will come out in resampling.

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:30.000
So if you fit the model once and you don't know

00:51:30.000 --> 00:51:32.000
and the model uses random numbers

00:51:32.000 --> 00:51:34.000
was that a good set of random numbers?

00:51:34.000 --> 00:51:36.000
You can get the effect of random numbers

00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:38.000
by doing cross-validation so that will

00:51:38.000 --> 00:51:40.000
measure the effect of it.

00:51:40.000 --> 00:51:42.000
The usage of it is

00:51:42.000 --> 00:51:44.000
we have inherited a lot of

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:46.000
things that I really

00:51:46.000 --> 00:51:48.000
haven't dealt with in Carrot.

00:51:48.000 --> 00:51:50.000
I came in with a whole list of okay we know what not to do

00:51:50.000 --> 00:51:52.000
a few things.

00:51:52.000 --> 00:51:54.000
For a while we had to figure out how

00:51:54.000 --> 00:51:56.000
when you are running in parallel to make sure you set

00:51:56.000 --> 00:51:58.000
the seeds inside the parallel

00:51:58.000 --> 00:52:00.000
workers to make sure those get set right.

00:52:00.000 --> 00:52:02.000
I have to say that with

00:52:02.000 --> 00:52:04.000
one or two exceptions everything is locked up

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:06.000
pretty tight.

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:08.000
If you set the seed

00:52:08.000 --> 00:52:10.000
before you do model tuning or something

00:52:10.000 --> 00:52:12.000
in 99% of the cases

00:52:12.000 --> 00:52:14.000
there is no issues with

00:52:14.000 --> 00:52:16.000
well the

00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:18.000
problem is like I said

00:52:18.000 --> 00:52:20.000
R often farms a lot

00:52:20.000 --> 00:52:22.000
out to other computing languages

00:52:22.000 --> 00:52:24.000
and the one

00:52:24.000 --> 00:52:26.000
I will tell you about one that

00:52:26.000 --> 00:52:28.000
is well known is

00:52:28.000 --> 00:52:30.000
if you are doing a support vector machine

00:52:30.000 --> 00:52:32.000
the main package that we use for that uses

00:52:32.000 --> 00:52:34.000
a C library called

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:36.000
LiveSVM

00:52:36.000 --> 00:52:38.000
and it turns out that

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:40.000
I am not sure why, Crayon usually

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:42.000
frowns on this, I am surprised this is a thing

00:52:42.000 --> 00:52:44.000
but it has its own random number

00:52:44.000 --> 00:52:46.000
generator in there. So if you are fitting

00:52:46.000 --> 00:52:48.000
a classification model

00:52:48.000 --> 00:52:50.000
especially if it is one that has

00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:52.000
really low event priorities

00:52:52.000 --> 00:52:54.000
or event prevalences

00:52:54.000 --> 00:52:56.000
if you run that model twice

00:52:56.000 --> 00:52:58.000
you are always going to get different answers

00:52:58.000 --> 00:53:00.000
but you get noticeably different answers in some cases.

00:53:00.000 --> 00:53:02.000
So that is something external to us

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:04.000
and I have over the years emailed the maintainer

00:53:04.000 --> 00:53:06.000
and they are like we did not write that library.

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:08.000
But the other

00:53:08.000 --> 00:53:10.000
thing that we realized is

00:53:10.000 --> 00:53:12.000
with deep learning we are trying to do a lot

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:14.000
leverage a lot of what comes with

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:16.000
TensorFlow and Torch

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:18.000
they do a lot on the GPU

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:20.000
and I am getting the idea that it is really

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:22.000
hard to set seeds in a GPU

00:53:22.000 --> 00:53:24.000
because none of them do it.

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:26.000
So we try

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:28.000
to lock that down as much as possible

00:53:28.000 --> 00:53:30.000
in the R packages

00:53:30.000 --> 00:53:32.000
talking to the people who manage those

00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:34.000
there were ways to set

00:53:34.000 --> 00:53:36.000
it by setting system environmental

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:38.000
variables but they have over

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:40.000
the years given us ways to set that

00:53:40.000 --> 00:53:42.000
so we have done as best as we can

00:53:42.000 --> 00:53:44.000
but chances are if you are using

00:53:44.000 --> 00:53:46.000
a GPU you cannot

00:53:46.000 --> 00:53:48.000
really guarantee that that

00:53:48.000 --> 00:53:50.000
is going to happen. But I think for the most

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:52.000
part it is pretty solid in terms of reproducibility.

00:53:54.000 --> 00:53:56.000
Anyone has

00:53:56.000 --> 00:53:58.000
more questions?

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:02.000
You mentioned that

00:54:02.000 --> 00:54:04.000
one of the possibilities when

00:54:04.000 --> 00:54:06.000
setting the engine was using

00:54:06.000 --> 00:54:08.000
Spark as an engine

00:54:08.000 --> 00:54:10.000
I would like to know

00:54:10.000 --> 00:54:12.000
how transparent is the transition

00:54:12.000 --> 00:54:14.000
for the user when using a

00:54:14.000 --> 00:54:16.000
vanilla engine, let's say Random Forest

00:54:16.000 --> 00:54:18.000
the more traditional implementation

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:20.000
if I want to switch to Spark

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:22.000
how much modification

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:24.000
of my code do I have to do

00:54:24.000 --> 00:54:26.000
or is more transparent

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:28.000
like just switching the engine?

00:54:28.000 --> 00:54:30.000
I've got good news and

00:54:30.000 --> 00:54:32.000
bad news. Which one would you like

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:34.000
first? Bad news.

00:54:34.000 --> 00:54:36.000
Right now

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:38.000
in setting models you can only just fit

00:54:38.000 --> 00:54:40.000
like with Parsnip a model

00:54:40.000 --> 00:54:42.000
with Spark. You can't tune them or resample

00:54:42.000 --> 00:54:44.000
them. And the reason

00:54:44.000 --> 00:54:46.000
for that is Spark DataFrames

00:54:46.000 --> 00:54:48.000
are really good at what they do but they are kind of

00:54:48.000 --> 00:54:50.000
hard to program against. So for example

00:54:50.000 --> 00:54:52.000
Spark DataFrame doesn't really have

00:54:52.000 --> 00:54:54.000
a way to tell you how many rows are in it

00:54:54.000 --> 00:54:56.000
because you would have to evaluate it to know

00:54:56.000 --> 00:54:58.000
and in some cases we need to know what that is.

00:54:58.000 --> 00:55:00.000
And so

00:55:00.000 --> 00:55:02.000
I think

00:55:02.000 --> 00:55:04.000
if you're using Spark, is there anybody

00:55:04.000 --> 00:55:06.000
else here that uses Spark a lot?

00:55:06.000 --> 00:55:08.000
Okay. So if it's

00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:10.000
of interest to you, what I would suggest you do

00:55:10.000 --> 00:55:12.000
is you go into Parsnip and put in

00:55:12.000 --> 00:55:14.000
issues about the TinyModels

00:55:14.000 --> 00:55:16.000
package

00:55:16.000 --> 00:55:18.000
or something like one of our

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:20.000
repos and say

00:55:20.000 --> 00:55:22.000
we need more

00:55:22.000 --> 00:55:24.000
comprehensive Spark support. So the bad news

00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:26.000
is you can't do a lot with

00:55:26.000 --> 00:55:28.000
Spark and TinyModels. The good news is it's really easy

00:55:28.000 --> 00:55:30.000
to know when that

00:55:30.000 --> 00:55:32.000
transition happens because there's no transition.

00:55:32.000 --> 00:55:34.000
So there's somebody who works

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:36.000
with us a lot named Edgar Ruiz

00:55:36.000 --> 00:55:38.000
and he's like the Spark genius. He probably knows more

00:55:38.000 --> 00:55:40.000
about Spark than most people on the planet

00:55:40.000 --> 00:55:42.000
and I think he has

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:44.000
grand designs for how

00:55:44.000 --> 00:55:46.000
you could make Spark work in almost everywhere

00:55:46.000 --> 00:55:48.000
in TinyModels. The problem

00:55:48.000 --> 00:55:50.000
is

00:55:50.000 --> 00:55:52.000
that complexity, we don't know how many people

00:55:52.000 --> 00:55:54.000
we don't know what the denominator is

00:55:54.000 --> 00:55:56.000
or we don't know what the numerator is. We know how many people

00:55:56.000 --> 00:55:58.000
roughly use Spark but we don't know how many

00:55:58.000 --> 00:56:00.000
people out of that want this

00:56:00.000 --> 00:56:02.000
and it would be quite a lot of work especially for

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:04.000
him and we don't know if it's

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:06.000
something we can do. So if

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:08.000
there are people out there that would like something like that

00:56:08.000 --> 00:56:10.000
you need to be vocal about it to us.

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:12.000
Yes.

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:14.000
Can I give you feedback about

00:56:14.000 --> 00:56:16.000
that topic?

00:56:16.000 --> 00:56:18.000
In my organization

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:20.000
I think

00:56:20.000 --> 00:56:22.000
that chicken and egg problem

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:24.000
that idea would be more

00:56:24.000 --> 00:56:26.000
developed. Like being able

00:56:26.000 --> 00:56:28.000
to code a model

00:56:28.000 --> 00:56:30.000
with a single implementation

00:56:30.000 --> 00:56:32.000
and then porting it to Spark

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:34.000
it would be like a killer application

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:36.000
for many organizations

00:56:36.000 --> 00:56:38.000
because even for people to use Python

00:56:38.000 --> 00:56:40.000
it might be rare.

00:56:40.000 --> 00:56:42.000
Coding in Stack Overflow is very easy

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:44.000
but the transitioning, the recoding

00:56:44.000 --> 00:56:46.000
of the Stack Overflow model to Spark

00:56:46.000 --> 00:56:48.000
it's more complicated

00:56:48.000 --> 00:56:50.000
so that kind of portability

00:56:50.000 --> 00:56:52.000
would be very important

00:56:52.000 --> 00:56:54.000
I didn't know it was

00:56:54.000 --> 00:56:56.000
possible until you mentioned it

00:56:56.000 --> 00:56:58.000
now.

00:56:58.000 --> 00:57:00.000
There's some limitations though

00:57:00.000 --> 00:57:02.000
so for example

00:57:02.000 --> 00:57:04.000
let's say you're doing

00:57:04.000 --> 00:57:06.000
you need to impute data

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:08.000
like you have missing data and you need to build an

00:57:08.000 --> 00:57:10.000
imputation model into your preprocessor

00:57:10.000 --> 00:57:12.000
to predict the missing values

00:57:12.000 --> 00:57:14.000
like if you're doing

00:57:14.000 --> 00:57:16.000
if you're doing nearest neighbor

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:18.000
imputation now you've got to save the entire

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:20.000
set at that point in the recipe

00:57:20.000 --> 00:57:22.000
so there's things that I'm not

00:57:22.000 --> 00:57:24.000
sure they're even feasible to do

00:57:24.000 --> 00:57:26.000
even if we try in Spark

00:57:26.000 --> 00:57:28.000
so if we end up having more

00:57:28.000 --> 00:57:30.000
substantial Spark support

00:57:30.000 --> 00:57:32.000
we don't know how to do this quite yet in documentation

00:57:32.000 --> 00:57:34.000
we're going to need to tell you

00:57:34.000 --> 00:57:36.000
when you can use this and when you can't

00:57:36.000 --> 00:57:38.000
we can have the function tell you

00:57:38.000 --> 00:57:40.000
when you execute it but we need

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:42.000
to figure out where that boundary is

00:57:42.000 --> 00:57:44.000
and how to document that boundary so that

00:57:44.000 --> 00:57:46.000
you're not frustrated like you see there's a

00:57:46.000 --> 00:57:48.000
